<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="23.[96,720,1795,2007]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
Similar to other peacock spiders in many respects, the genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Otto &amp; Hill" authorityYear="2017" box="[241,368,1824,1850]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Saratus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesperus">
<emphasis box="[241,368,1824,1850]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">S. hesperus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males and females are quite different. Emergent instars are boldly spotted and the deep blue or purple of the fan is based on layering of the cuticle rather than scale structure. The species name, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Otto &amp; Hill" authorityYear="2017" box="[176,274,1950,1975]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Saratus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesperus">
<emphasis box="[176,274,1950,1975]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">hesperus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is based on the Greek name for the Evening Star (
<emphasis box="[256,351,1981,2006]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Eσπερος</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
